PROFILE:
KAREN
FISCHER,
GEOLOGY

The
Rewards
of
Disasters

Professor
of
Geology
Karen
Fischer
has

shaken
things
up
in
both
her
roles
as
scientist

and
teacher.
A
seismologist
and

geophysicist,
Fischer
researches
seismic

waves
in
an
attempt
to
understand
the

earth's
interior.
As
a
teacher,
Fischer
leads

one
introductory
geology
course,
Geology

58
(Physical
Processes
and
Environmental

Consequences),
along
with
two
upper-level

classes,
Geology
161
(Solid
Earth

Geophysics)
and
Geology
165
(Earthquake
Seismology).

When
Fischer
decided
to
go
into
science,

it
was
no
surprise
to
her
friends
and
family.

Science
was
the
family
business.
In
addition

to
both
of
her
parents
being
physicists
and

both
of
her
grandfathers
chemists,
her
brother

is
an
environmental
physicist.
Born
in

Cambridge,
Massachusetts,

Fischer
graduated
from
Yale
in

1983.
She
received
her
PhD
from

MIT
in
1988
and
after
a
post

doctoral
program
at
Columbia,

became
an
assistant
professor
at

Brown
in
1990.
Why
geology?

Fischer
entered
college

determined
not
to
follow
her

family's
scientifically-inclined

footsteps,
complete
with
plans
to

become
a
composer
of

contemporary
music.
But
during

her
sophomore
year
at
Yale,
she

enrolled
in
an
introduction
to

geology
course.

"In
geology
I
found
a
place

where
I
could
apply
science
that

really
interested
me
a
place

where
you
can
talk
about
physics
but
in
a

way
so
you
could
apply
it
to
mountains
and

earthquakes,"
she
said.
Explaining
why
she

became
a
teacher,
Fischer
said
she
views

teaching
as
"a
way
of
keeping
my
skills

really
sharp
as
my
views
are
constantly

challenged
by
people
who
don't
necessarily

share
the
same
assumptions."

"The
reason
I
like
teaching
at
Brown
is

because
the
students
are
really
smart,

enthusiastic,
and
they
think
independently

and
critically,"
Fischer
said.
"They
really

analyze
what
I'm
saying
and
have
a

refreshing
way
of
looking
at
problems.

That's
really
good
for
me
it
keeps
me
on

my
toes."

Fischer
enjoys
her
involvement
in
the

Women
in
Science
and
Engineering
(WISE)

organization,
and
rims
a
WISE
affinity
group

with
Professors
Jan
Tullis
and
Annie

Schmidt.
The
three
science
professors
meet

with
undergraduates
to
provide
practical

and
emotional
support
on
such
subjects
as

how
to
apply
to
grad
school,
along
with

issues
that
affect
women
going
into
science.

In
Brown's
geology
department,
one-half

of
the
undergraduates
and
one-half
of
the

graduates
are
female.
This
was
a
big
contrast

to
Fischer's
college
days
when
only
one

tenth
of
her
geology
department
were

women.
Speculating
on
this
relatively
recent

increase,
Fischer
said,
"Geology
was
a
field

traditionally
dominated
by
men,
so
it
was

less
open
to
females.
But
with
a
few
more

women
in
leadership
roles,
it
became
easier

for
younger
women
to
come
along."

Despite
her
strong
links
to
the
science

community,
Fischer
does
not
gear
her

courses
exclusively
toward
science

concentrators.
Students
in
her
Geo
58
course

not
only
study
the
physical
causes
of
natural

disasters,
but
also
examine
public
policy

approaches
to
hazard
mitigation.
Fischer

integrates
these
two
approaches.
When

studying
landslides
students
not
only
learn

the
formulas
for
slope
stability,
but
also

discuss
steps
communities
take
to
protect

themselves
from
landslide
damage.

Avijit
Sen
'96,
a
former
Geo
58
class

member,
described
Fischer
as
"very

approachable
and
encouraging."
He

appreciated
the
class's
emphasis
on
the

practical
application
of
geological

techniques.
"We
took
two
great
field
trips

where
we
looked
at
how
different
coastal

areas
eroded.
Also,
I
learned
how
to
use
tools

that
field
geologists
use,"
Sen
said.
"Actually,

I
learned
how
to
apply
more
sophisticated

techniques
in
Geo
58
than
in
upper-level

geological
classes
I
later
took."
